This paper deals with a classification method for incoming pieces of evidence in Dempster-Shafer theory, which is a popular approach in artificial intelligence and machine learning for dealing with uncertain and incomplete information. The paper also mentions clustering and specification, which are common techniques in data mining and machine learning. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also involves computational complexity analysis, which is a topic in theoretical computer science, making cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) a likely sub-category as well. The paper's focus on prototypes and fast classification could also make it relevant to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.IT (Information Theory).
